  "prompt": "What prove the existence of the boundary between the crust and the mantle?",
  "response": "The existence of the boundary between the Earth's crust and mantle, known as the Mohorovi\u010di\u0107 discontinuity or simply the \"Moho,\" is primarily evidenced by seismic data. The key observations leading to the identification of the Moho are:\n\n1. **Seismic Wave Velocity Changes**: During an earthquake, seismic waves travel through the Earth. When these waves pass from the crust into the mantle, there is a noticeable increase in their velocity. This change is indicative of a transition between two layers of different compositions and densities. The crust is composed of lighter materials, while the mantle is made up of denser and more rigid rocks.\n\n2. **Refraction and Reflection of Seismic Waves**: Some seismic waves are refracted or reflected when they hit the Moho due to the contrast in material properties. This creates a distinct pattern on seismograms, allowing geophysicists to map the boundary.\n\n3. **Seismic Tomography**: Advances in seismic tomography have provided detailed images of the Earth's interior, confirming the presence of the Moho. This technique uses measurements from a network of seismic stations to construct 3D models of the Earth's subsurface.\n\n4. **Laboratory and Field Studies**: Rock samples from the crust and upper mantle have been analyzed for their physical and chemical properties. These studies support the differences in composition and structure observed at the Moho.\n\nThese lines of evidence collectively confirm the existence of the Mohorovi\u010di\u0107 discontinuity as a distinct boundary separating the Earth's crust from its mantle.",
